A Manager Server Process is only started when you create a Manager. from multiprocessing import Manager manager = Manager() # Starts a manager server process If program is simply from multithreading import Process ,here creates child processes,no manager server process is started.In multitheading, the parent process creates child process directly (using OS mechanism such as fork/spawn), not through a manager server process. A server process can hold python objects and allows other processes to manipulate them using proxies. multiprocessing.Manager this Manager class controls a server process. managers provides a way to create data that can be shared between different processes. managers are more flexible than shared memory but slower. Relations Parent Process | +---- Manager Server Process | +---- Child Process 1 | +---- Child Process 2 The child process can't directly access the shared object which lives inside the Manger Server Process manager=Manager() shared_list=manager.list() child process accessing shared resource like this, Child Process | | proxy request v Manager Server Process | | updates actual list v shared_list Why it is called a server? Holds the real objects Waits for requests Other processes connects to it Performs operations on behalf of the those child processes. example: import multiprocessing def print_records(records): """ function to print record(tuples) in records(list) """ for record in records: print("Name: {0}
Score: {1}
".format(record[0], record[1])) def insert_record(record, records): """ function to add a new record to records(list) """ records.append(record) print("New record added!
") if __name__ == '__main__': with multiprocessing.Manager() as manager: # creating a list in server process memory records = manager.list([('Sam', 10), ('Adam', 9), ('Kevin',9)]) # new record to be inserted in records new_record = ('Jeff', 8) # creating new processes p1 = multiprocessing.Process(target=insert_record, args=(new_record, records)) p2 = multiprocessing.Process(target=print_records, args=(records,)) # running process p1 to insert new record p1.start() p1.join() # running process p2 to print records p2.start() p2.join() output New record added! Name: Sam Score: 10 Name: Adam Score: 9 Name: Kevin Score: 9 Name: Jeff Score: 8 First of all, we create a manager object using: with multiprocessing.Manager() as manager: All the lines under with statement block are under the scope of manager object. Then, we create a list records in server process memory using: records = manager.list([('Sam', 10), ('Adam', 9), ('Kevin',9)]) Similarly, you can create a dictionary as manager.dict method.
